  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are numerous statutes that address money laundering in various jurisdictions around the world. Here are some key examples:\n\n### United States\n1. **Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) of 1970**: Requires financial institutions to report certain transactions and keep records that could be used to identify money laundering activities.\n2. **Money Laundering Control Act (MLCA) of 1986**: Established money laundering as a federal crime and outlined penalties for those involved in such activities.\n3. **Patriot Act of 2001**: Enhanced previous anti-money laundering (AML) laws by requiring financial institutions to implement more robust AML programs and to monitor for suspicious activities.\n\n### European Union\n1. **EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives**: A series of directives (the latest being the 6th AML Directive) that harmonize AML regulations across EU member states, requiring them to implement measures to prevent money laundering and terrorist financing.\n2. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**: Although not a statute, the FATF sets international standards for combating money laundering, which many EU countries incorporate into their national laws.\n\n### United Kingdom\n1. **Proceeds of Crime Act (POCA) 2002**: The primary legislation in the UK for combating money laundering, making it a criminal offense to launder or help launder the proceeds of any crime.\n2. **Money Laundering Regulations 2017**: Implements the EU\u2019s 4th AML Directive, requiring businesses to conduct due diligence on their customers and report suspicious activities.\n\n### Canada\n1. **Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act (PCMLTFA)**: Establishes the legal framework for AML and counter-terrorist financing in Canada, requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions and maintain records.\n\n### Australia\n1. **Anti-Money Laundering and Counter-Terrorism Financing Act 2006 (AML/CTF Act)**: Sets out the regulatory requirements for detecting and preventing money laundering and terrorism financing in Australia.\n\n### International Standards\n1. **Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations**: Provides a comprehensive framework of measures to combat money laundering and terrorist financing, which many countries adopt into their national laws.\n\nThese examples illustrate the global effort to combat money laundering through legislation and regulatory frameworks. Each country may have its own specific laws and regulations, but they generally align with international standards set by organizations like the FATF.",
